@node "PreRelease" "Pre-Release Informations"

                       @{b}Pre-Release Information
                      ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

FAME is a brand new MailBox program which seems to be very popular
and FAMEous as we can see from the very positive reactions we receive
daily.

We already have many bug-reports and suggestions and we believe we will
get tons more from the very first release onwards.

We work hard on fixing all the reported bugs and implementing suggestions
as best we can, but it's impossible to do it all at the same time.

The same with the documents.

The documents are not complete at all... we have to enhance and enlarge
the documents as long as we have to do this with the FAME programs.

You have bought FAME at an early stage and because of this not everything
written here will be 100% correct but we are working on it.


@{u}@{b}Known not described parts in FAME.guide@{uu}@{ub}

 - None.

@endnode

@node MPGUI_Basics "Mainpart: general topics"

                           @{b}General topics of MainPart
                          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

This chapter explains how to operate on the main screen of a FAME Node.

Once a node gets started, a screen pops up where a BBS SysOp can watch
a 100% copy of all current user activity, and where a SysOp may log on
himself.

You may start a node by setting up special startup flags for each node at
the FAME System Editor, or you may start it by clicking on its Node
button in the FAME @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} window.  The Node buttons are placed on the
leftmost position of the FAME @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} window.  This group of buttons is
top-labelled "Node#".  More about starting a Node is detailed in the FAME
@{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} manual.

If a Node is started and "awaiting call", but no screen pops up, then you
should check the state of the "iconified" button at the Node's Screen
setup of the FAME System Editor.  This button tells the @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} if a node
shall be started in iconified state.

If you start working at the FAME Node screen, note that FAME has the
feature of asynchronous windows.  This programming method does not put a
window into sleep mode (busy-pointer) if another FAME window is opened or
activated.  This means that all node action can be performed anytime; no
matter if the Node Window is active or not.  Any console input will be
handled to the Node's main window if the curently active FAME window has
no use for it.  For example, if you open and activate another FAME window
(e.g.  the iconify window), hitting F1 while a user is logged on will put
him/her into SysOp chat, no matter which of both windows is active.

Once a Node screen pops up, there are two possible things you may see:

In the first case, the await (main title) display appears, where you see a
FAME logo at the top, and twenty buttons, presenting the equivalents to
the twenty installed F-Key functions you may use now.  These commands are
executed by hitting one of the F1 to F10 (gadget equivalents on the left)
or Shift-F1 to Shift-F10 (gadgets on the right side) keys.

In the second case, when a user is logged on, the title display is turned
off, and you are directly watching the BBS main process where you can see
what the user is doing and seeing.  You may directly interact within the
display as if you were the user.  Note that accidently typing into this
display may confuse or disturb a user, because both yours and the user's
input get mixed.  Another way to watch a user is to let the FAME @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"}
open a Node Spy Window for you.  Please refer to the FAME @{"Server" link "Server.guide/Main"} manual
for more details.

The F-Key functions differ if the Node is in "online" state. For example,
the "Sysop Login" function (F1) is not useful if there is already someone
logged on. In login state, the F1 key activates the SysOp chat instead.

The Node screen may be also used to help or to chat with a user, or for
local logons.  Beware of the fact that an opened node screen will
significantly reduce text output speed at the remote (serial) side.  Even
if you have installed a graphics accelerator board, the user will notice a
speed difference.  In order not to annoy users, and in order to let a
possible hacker think that he isn't watched by the SysOp, Node screens
should only be opened if they are really needed.  

Small spy windows allow much faster scrolling if placed on a screen with
only two or four colours, or on the display of a graphics enhancer board.
Beyond that, with systems which have for example 20 Nodes running with
users logged on, opening all Node screens would bog down the system so
much that the whole system would suffer under the high CPU load, and
everything would slow down.  All screen/window and font settings may be
configured within the FAME System Editor.

In online mode, the node Screen (or better, the Node's main window)
presents a complete interactive ANSI terminal interface.  The Amiga
console.device is used for the terminal emulation, including all
console.device specific ANSI code sequences.

The Node's main window ("the node window") is invisible, because it's a
borderless backdrop window.  By default, it's size equals the whole screen
(without the screen title bar).  The node window size and position may be
set up using the FAME System Editor.  This is useful if you want, for
example, to place additional guest windows on the Node screen.  FAME Node
screens can be made public.

The ANSI emulation displays texts using a range of special commands which
control many text output characteristics, like text colours, text
attributes, scroll borders, text positioning and formatting, screen beeps
and many more.

A user on the remote side can't send, for example, F-Key commands. These
key commands are only accepted from the local computer (the console), of
course.

While being in login mode, the node may be in one of two states.  The
first one is the wait state, where the BBS waits for a user command input.
This wait state is attended by a prompt, like this:

MyBBS @{fg shine}<<@{fg fill}1@{fg text}: @{fg fill}<NewUserConf>@{fg shine}>> Menu @{fg fill}>@{fg shine}: @{fg text}@{bg fill} @{bg back}

In this state, FAME has executed all commands and awaits further
instructions from the current user.  At this moment, we tend to say that
the user is in "the main menu", or at "the main prompt".

The second state is when FAME is executing a command.  At this moment,
user inputs have no immediate effect to the BBS, but the currently
executed command may prompt the user for some inputs.  A running command
completely takes over the current Node, including all input and output
handling.  The Node is frozen as long as the command is running.  The
command itself may operate on the Node as if it was a part of it.  These
commands may be FAME internal commands, or any of an unlimited number of
additionally installable external programs.  These external BBS commands
may perform much more than one simple command.  They may present an
interface between the FAME BBS, the user, and a third-party system.

More about the difference between FAME awaiting input or executing a
command can be found in the @{"Screen Close Gadget" link MPGUI_NodeClose}
chapter.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node MPGUI_FKeys "Mainpart: the Function keys"

                         @{b}The function keys of MainPart
                        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Each F1 to F10 and Shift-F1 to Shift-F10 keys are always available, but
some of them have different functions for both Await and Online modes.

@{b}Await Mode Function Keys:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

 @{fg fill}@{b}F1@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- SysOp Login.@{ub} The login procedure will get truncated; no need to enter
      username or password.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F2@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Local Login.@{ub} Your guests & friends may log on this way. The login
      procedure will ask for his/her username, but not for the password.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F3@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Remote Login.@{ub} Starts an immediate Connect attempt. Used if a remote
      user is already connected with your telephone line (e.g. by voice) 
      and wants to log on now. The user's modem must also try to connect. 
      This is done just by dialing nothing (ATD). FAME sends ATA (answer 
      call).

 @{fg fill}@{b}F4@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Reserve For A User.@{ub} With this command you may reserve the Node for a
      special user. If somebody logs on, FAME will check if he/she is the
      special user you reserved the Node for. If not, FAME tells him/her
      that the current Node is not available at the moment and hangs up.
      SysOp Logins override user reservations. After any user has 
      successfully logged in, the user reservation is flushed.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F5@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Conference Access Editor.@{ub} This function key calls the built-in
      @{"Conference Access Editor" link MPGUI_ConfAccEd}, where you may define your conference
      access setups.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F6@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Internal User Editor.@{ub} Not as comfortable as the module User Editor,
      but keeps the SysOp at the main window and disables any user input 
      and output. The user interface (the serial port) is completely 
      halted while you're using the internal User Editor. The internal 
      User Editor is mostly used for quick online user access editing.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F7@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Chat Toggle.@{ub} Activates the AvailChat flag. If this flag is set, the
      SysOp states himself as being available for chat calls. If a user
      requests a SysOp chat while this flag is inactive, he/she will always
      get the answer that the SysOp is not available for chat at the 
      moment, while you (as SysOp) never get disturbed.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F8@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Modem Init.@{ub} Sends the modem init string again. Useful if you have 
      done some changes (e.g. if the modem was turned off for a while).

 @{fg fill}@{b}F9@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Exit Node On-Hook.@{ub} Shuts down the Node and releases the telephone 
      line.

@{fg fill}@{b}F10@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Exit Node Off-Hook.@{ub} Shuts down the Node, but keeps the phone line 
      busy.


@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F1@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Fast Sysop Login.@{ub} Same as @{i}Sysop Login@{ui}, but the login procedure gets
      truncated to a minimum, so that you reach the main prompt as soon as
      possible.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F2@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Fast Local Login.@{ub} Same as @{i}Local Login@{ui}, but the login procedure gets
      truncated for your guests this time.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F3@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Fast Remote Login.@{ub} Same as @{i}Remote Login@{ui}, but with a truncated login
      procedure for the remote user.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F4@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Status & Commands.@{ub} Opens the Status & Commands window.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F5@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- System Editor.@{ub} Pops the server screen to front and loads the FAME
      System Editor.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F6@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Module User Editor.@{ub} Starts the standard GUI/MUI User Editor module.
      The User Editor Module is a standalone FAME add-on, used for general
      user account editing.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F7@{ub}@{fg text} - (unused)

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F8@{ub}@{fg text} - (unused)

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F9@{ub}@{fg text} - (unused)

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F10@{ub}@{fg text}@{b}- Iconify Window.@{ub} Opens the @{"Node Close" link MPGUI_NodeClose} (iconify) options window.


@{b}Online Mode Function Keys:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

In online mode, the function keys have different commands assigned and are
only available if the Node is at the main prompt, or if the currently
executed command/door handles SysOp function keys correctly.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F1@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Start/End Sysop Chat.@{ub} Puts the online user into the SysOp chat mode,
      where user and SysOp share the whole screen for an online dialogue.
      <BBSLOCATION>/Conferences/<ActConfName>/StartChat.txt is displayed
      as chat introduction text.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F2@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Time +10.@{ub} Adds 10 minutes to the remaining online time of the current
      online user for this day.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F3@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Time -10.@{ub} Subtracts 10 minutes from the remaining online time of the
      current online user for this day.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F4@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Start User Capture.@{ub} Starts user action capture recording. If a 
      potential hacker snoops around while your doorbell rings, don't 
      panic; just activate this handy button. The user's activities get 
      captured then, so that you may control all performed user action 
      later. The Checkmark confirms the capture activation. Note that 
      capturing things for long periods (days or longer) may consume much 
      harddisk space. The capture file is named
      "<BBSLOCATION>/Capture/<USERNUMBER>/<DATE>" -where BBSLOCATION is the
      FAME: path, USERNUMBER is a sub directory named by the user's slot 
      number and DATE is the capture file itself, named by the date of 
      opening. Multiple capture starts within the same day will produce 
      multiple files with file name suffixes ".1", ".2" and so on.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F5@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- NewShell.@{ub} Opens a new Shell window on the Node screen, using a 
      defined FROM script for.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F6@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- UserEdOn.@{ub} Starts the internal User Editor and loads the current 
      online user on startup for an immediate edit. Serial input and 
      output is disabled as long as you're in the User Editor.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F7@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Chat toggle.@{ub} Activates the AvailChat flag. If this flag is set, the
      SysOp states himself as being available for chat calls. If a user
      requests a SysOp chat while this flag is inactive, he/she will always
      get the answer that the SysOp is not available for chat at the 
      moment, while you (as SysOp) never get disturbed.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F8@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Toggle SerIn.@{ub} Disables/enables serial input. When turned off, the 
      online user cannot send any further input. Useful if you want to 
      perform some special online action while a user is online and you 
      want to protect the BBS against his/her influence as long as you're 
      working.

 @{fg fill}@{b}F9@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Toggle SerOut.@{ub} Similar to "SerIn", but disables/enables serial output
      instead. That means, the user no longer receives any echos anyway;
      he/she is blind now and can't see what's going on as long as you 
      don't reactivate this flag.

@{fg fill}@{b}F10@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Drop User or Exit Node/Door.@{ub} Drops a running door. If no door is 
      active, the Node hangs up. If no user is online, the Node shuts down.


@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F1@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Start/End Sysop Chat.@{ub} Same as F1, but displays StartChat2.txt as chat
      introduction text instead.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F2@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Free for doors.@{ub} Door developers may install any door-related sysop
      command here.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F3@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Free for doors.@{ub} Door developers may install any door-related sysop
      command here.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F4@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Display Text.@{ub} Opens a file requester which asks for a text (ANSI-)
      file to display in the Node's main window.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F5@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- Send File.@{ub} This Key opens a file requester, asking for any file you
      want to send (upload) to the user right now, no matter where the user
      is or what he does.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F6@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- SysOp Access (+ UsEdOn).@{ub} Grants temporary Sysop access and loads the
      current user into the internal User Editor. Serial input and output 
      is turned off as long as you're in the User Editor. Hitting Shift-F6 
      again will remove the temporary SysOp access.

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F7@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- (unused)

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F8@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- (unused)

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F9@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}- (unused)

@{fg shine}^@{fg fill}@{b}F10@{ub}@{fg text}@{b}- Fast Shutdown.@{ub} The Node hangs up and shuts down immediately. If a 
      door is running, only the door is shut down.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node MPGUI_Menus "Mainpart: menu commands"

                           @{b}Menu commands of MainPart
                          ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

As long as a Node is in Await state, there are some additional menu
commands installed.  The menus become inactive when a user logs on,
because online menu operations would noticably slow down the Node for the
user.

The following menus are available:

@{b}@{fg fill}System@{fg text}@{ub}

 - @{b}About@{ub} (Amiga-a)

   Pops up the well-known about information window.

 - @{b}Quick Iconify@{ub} (Amiga-i)

   Immediate iconify. The node gets iconified immediately without
   opening the iconify window first.

 - @{b}Exit Node@{ub} (Amiga-e)

   Shuts down the node and releases the telephone line.

 - @{b}Exit Node (off hook)@{ub} (Amiga-x)

   Shuts down the Node and keeps the line busy (modem off-hook).


@{b}@{fg fill}Login@{fg text}@{ub}

 - @{b}Sysop Login@{ub} (F1 or Amiga-s)

   With this command you may quickly log on as the SysOp. The login
   procedure will get truncated; no need to enter username or password.

 - @{b}Local Login@{ub} (F2 or Amiga-l)

   Your guests & friends may log on this way. The login procedure will
   ask for his/her username, but not for the password.

 - @{b}Remote Login@{ub} (F3 or Amiga-.)

   Starts an immediate Connect attempt. Used if a remote user is already
   connected with your telephone line (e.g. by voice) and wants to log
   on now. The user's modem must also try to connect. This is done just
   by dialing nothing (ATD). FAME sends ATA (answer call).

 - @{b}Fast Sysop Login@{ub} (Shift-F1 or Amiga-1)

   Same as @{i}Sysop Login@{ui}, but the login procedure gets truncated to a
   minimum, so that you reach the main prompt as soon as possible.

 - @{b}Fast Local Login@{ub} (Shift-F2 or Amiga-2)

   Same as @{i}Local Login@{ui}, but the login procedure gets truncated for
   your guests this time.

 - @{b}Fast Remote Login@{ub} (Shift-F3 or Amiga-3)

   Same as @{i}Remote Login@{ui}, but with a truncated login procedure for
   the remote user.

@{b}@{fg fill}Extra@{fg text}@{ub}

 - @{b}User Reserve@{ub} (F4 or Amiga-r)

   With this command you may reserve the Node for a special user.
   If somebody logs on, FAME will check if he/she is the special
   user you reserved the Node for. If not, FAME tells him/her that
   the current Node is not available at the moment and hangs up.
   SysOp Logins override user reservations. After any user has
   successfully logged in, the user reservation is flushed.

 - @{b}Chat Toggle@{ub} (F7 or Amiga-c)

   Activates the AvailChat flag. If this flag is set, the SysOp states
   himself as being available for chat calls. If a user requests a
   SysOp chat while this flag is inactive, he/she will always get
   the answer that the SysOp is not available for chat at the moment,
   while you (as SysOp) never get disturbed.

 - @{b}User Editor@{ub} (F6 or Amiga-u)

   Starts the internal User Editor. Not as comfortable as the module
   User Editor, but keeps the SysOp at the main window and disables
   any user input and output. The user interface (the serial port)
   is completely halted while you're using the internal User Editor.
   The internal User Editor is mostly used for quick online user
   access editing.

 - @{b}Module User Editor@{ub} (Shift-F6 or Amiga-d)

   Starts the standard GUI/MUI User Editor module. The User Editor
   Module is a standalone FAME add-on, used for general user account
   editing.

 - @{b}System Editor@{ub} (Shift-F5 or Amiga-o)

   Pops the server screen to front and loads the FAME System Editor.

 - @{b}Init Modem@{ub} (F8 or Amiga-m)

   Sends the modem init string again. Useful if you have done some
   changes (e.g. the modem was turned off for a while).

 - @{b}Status & Commands@{ub} (Help, Shift-F4 or Amiga-n)

   Opens the Status & Commands window.

@endnode

