@node MPGUI_Status_Commands "Mainpart: the Status & Commands window"

                          @{b}The Status & Commands window
                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The Help key opens the Status & Commands window. At this control panel you 
may get some additional information and order some BBS action.

The upper half of this window shows up some information about the current
online user (if there is any).
The text fields at the left side are only filled if a user is currently
online. The right-handed texts show information about the current or the
last online user (if the Node is in await state again). The following texts
are visible here:

  ,-----------------------------------------------------------------.
  | @{fg fill}NAME:@{fg text} <the user's name>                                         |
  | @{fg fill}LOC.:@{fg text} <his/her location>                                        |
  | @{fg fill}CITY:@{fg text} <city>                                                    |
  | @{fg fill}PASS:@{fg text} <password>   @{fg fill}NUM.:@{fg text} - <user number>                        |
  | @{fg fill}CONF:@{fg text} <conference access string> @{fg fill}LVL :@{fg text} - <user level>           |
  | @{fg fill}PHO.:@{fg text} <phone number>  @{fg fill}RAT.:@{fg text} - <file ratio>                      |
  | @{fg fill}LAST:@{fg text} <date & time of last call> @{fg fill}BAUD:@{fg text} - <connect baud rate>    |
  `-----------------------------------------------------------------'

The lower half of the window contains several gadgets:

 - @{b}System Editor@{ub}

   Pops the server screen to front and loads the FAME System Editor.

 - @{b}Fast Editor@{ub}

   The same as @{i}System Editor@{ui}, but the System Editor will skip
   path/file checking on startup. From time to time, it may be
   useful to call the System Editor the normal way once in order
   to check if everything is up to date.

 - @{b}Reload Config@{ub}

   Reloads the Node configuration, if, for example, some changes
   have been done from within the System Editor. Not every setup
   may be changed without shutting down the Node. External processes
   may use the FAME tool communication port to perform additional
   online reconfiguration.

 - @{b}UserEd Module@{ub}

   Starts the standard GUI/MUI User Editor module. The User Editor
   Module is a standalone FAME add-on, used for general user account
   editing.

 - @{b}Chat@{ub}

   Puts the online user into the SysOp chat mode, where user and
   SysOp share the whole screen for an online dialogue (the F1 and
   Shift-F1 keys do the same).

 - @{b}Time +@{ub}

   Adds 10 minutes to the remaining online time of the current online
   user for this day.

 - @{b}Time -@{ub}

   Subtracts 10 minutes from the remaining online time of the current
   online user for this day.

 - @{b}View@{ub}

   Display Text. Opens a file requester which asks for a text (ANSI-)
   file to display in the Node's main window.

 - @{b}Iconify@{ub}

   Pops up the iconify window.

 - @{b}UsEdit@{ub}

   Starts the internal User Editor. Not as comfortable as the module
   User Editor, but keeps the SysOp at the main window and disables
   any user input and output. The user interface (the serial port)
   is completely halted while you're using the internal User Editor.
   The internal User Editor is mostly used for quick online user
   access editing.

 - @{b}UsEdOn@{ub}

   Same as @{i}UsEdit@{ui}, but also loads the current online user on startup
   for an immediate edit.

 - @{b}HangUp@{ub}

   Fast Shutdown. The Node hangs up and shuts down immediately.
   If a door is running, only the door is shut down.

 @{b}Checkmark Buttons:

 - Capture@{ub}

   Starts user action capture recording. If a potential hacker snoops
   around while your doorbell rings, don't panic and activate this
   handy button. The user's activities get captured then, so that
   you may control all performed user action later. The Checkmark
   confirms the capture activation. Note that capturing things for
   long periods (days or longer) may consume much harddisk space.
   The capture file is named "<BBSLOCATION>/Capture/<USERNUMBER>/<DATE>"
   -where BBSLOCATION is the FAME: path, USERNUMBER is a sub directory
   named by the user's slot number and DATE is the capture file itself,
   named by the date of opening. Multiple capture starts within the
   same day will produce multiple files with file name suffixes ".1",
   ".2" and so on.

 - @{b}ChatTgl@{ub}

   Activates the AvailChat flag. If this flag is set, the SysOp states
   himself as being available for chat calls. If a user requests a
   SysOp chat while this flag is inactive, he/she will always get
   the answer that the SysOp is not available for chat at the moment,
   while you (as SysOp) never get disturbed.

 - @{b}SerIn@{ub}

   Enables serial input. If this flag is turned off, the user cannot
   send any further input. Useful if you want to perform some special
   online action while a user is online and you want to protect the
   BBS against his/her influence as long as you're working.

 - @{b}SerOut@{ub}

   Similar to "SerIn", serial output is disabled. That means, the user
   no longer receives any echos anyway, meaning that he/she is blind
   now and can't see what's going on as long as you don't reactivate
   this flag.

 - @{b}Close Gadget@{ub}

   Closes the Status & Commands window.

With the exception of checkmark buttons, every gadget will also close the
Status & Commands window.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node MPGUI_NodeClose "Mainpart: the Node Close window"

                             @{b}The Node Close window
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

On the upper left corner of the screen you'll see the Node Close gadget,
placed inside the screen title bar.  This gadget opens a window where you
may choose to drop a door, logout a user or iconify/shutdown the whole
Node.

The Node close gadget opens a window which offers three different actions:

 - @{b}Iconify Node@{ub}

   Close the Node's screen, if possible (no visitor windows present)

 - @{b}Drop User Or Exit Node/Door@{ub}

   While any door program is running on this node, selecting this gadget
   will cause FAME to send a door abort request to the currently running
   door.  If this (FIM type) door fulfils the FAME door programming
   guidelines, it will immediately shut down itself and let the user
   return to the BBS main prompt.  If this doesn't happen, the door is
   either poorly written or simply hung-up.  You may force dropping the
   door by clicking on this gadget again.  In this case, FAME drops the
   door no matter what's actually going on.  Be careful when using doors
   which do not shut down if ordered by FAME to do so.  You'd risk
   problems which may occur on shutting down a door the hardcore way
   (clicking this button twice).  If FAME forces a door shutdown, the door
   may have still some system or FAME BBS data in use.  The result may be
   some trouble.

   If a user is logged on and there is no door currently running, this
   gadget will drop the user itself, instead of a door.  The modem is hung
   up immediately.  This behaviour is sometimes called "user kick".

   If there is nobody online, this gadget will execute it's third action
   level:  the Node gets completely shut down.  With the FAME System
   Editor you may configure if the Node's modem shall be switched to Off
   Hook or On Hook state when shutting down the node.  Off Hook (displayed
   as "node shutdown OH" in the Server's Node activity line) will hold the
   telephone line busy once the Node is closed down, while On Hook would
   release the telephone line (hang-up).  Holding a line busy signals
   further callers about that the BBS won't stay offline for a longer
   period, so that retrying to call the BBS was worthy.

   If a Node is shut down, the serial device of the Node gets released;
   other (terminal) programs may use the line from now on.

 - @{b}Cancel@{ub}

   Oops.. :^)

 - @{b}Close Gadget@{ub}

   Same effect as the @{i}Cancel@{ui} gadget.

@endnode

